The closure of a subset A in a topological space X is the smallest closed set containing A. A closed set is the complement of an open set. In this case, the subset A = {1}.

First, let's find the closed sets in the topological space X. The open sets are {∅, {1}, {2}, {1,2}}. The complements of these open sets are:

1. X \ ∅ = {1, 2}
2. X \ {1} = {2}
3. X \ {2} = {1}
4. X \ {1, 2} = ∅

So, the closed sets are {∅, {1}, {2}, {1, 2}}.

Now, we want to find the smallest closed set containing the subset A = {1}. The closed set {1} contains the subset {1} and is the smallest closed set containing {1}.

Therefore, the closure of the subset {1} is {1}.
